  "chunk_index": 12,
  "summary": "Megan Barnard informs Hercule Poirot that her sister, Betty, had a volatile relationship with Donald Fraser. Megan explains that Betty frequently lied to avoid conflict with Donald, specifically regarding her outings. A month prior to her death, Donald became furious after discovering Betty had lied about visiting a friend in Hastings when she was actually in Eastbourne with a married man. Megan notes that Betty's habit of lying served as a defense mechanism, and she suspects Betty may have avoided the man to prevent further arguments with Donald.\n\nMegan brings a pale and distraught Donald Fraser to the kitchen to speak with Poirot. After Poirot provides him with brandy to steady his nerves, Donald reveals that Betty had told him she was going to St. Leonards with a friend. Although he initially believed her, he grew suspicious and traveled to St. Leonards at eight o'clock to watch for her. Upon seeing no sign of her, he panicked and searched hotels, restaurants, and the harbor in Hastings before eventually returning home around midnight.\n\nDuring this conversation, Inspector Croome arrives from London. Poirot introduces Megan and Donald to the inspector, noting that he has been gathering information to better understand the case. As Poirot retreats to the living room, he remarks to Hastings that he is surprised by the \"murderer's goodness,\" a comment that leaves Hastings confused.",
